[GPT]: I have now extracted the full implementation of should_strip_auth, which is the critical function for determining whether Authorization headers are stripped during redirects, especially from HTTP to HTTPS.

Analysis of should_strip_auth (requests/sessions.py, lines 127–159):

- The function returns True (strip auth) if the hostname changes.
- For HTTP→HTTPS on the same host and standard ports (80→443), it returns False (do not strip auth).
- For redirects where the scheme does not change and ports are default, it also returns False.
- Otherwise, it returns changed_port or changed_scheme.

This means: If a request is redirected from HTTP to HTTPS on the same host and standard ports, the Authorization header is NOT stripped and will be sent to the HTTPS destination.

This is a known security risk: If an attacker can cause a redirect from HTTP to HTTPS, the Authorization header (potentially containing credentials) will be sent to the new HTTPS endpoint, which may be controlled by an attacker (e.g., via DNS rebinding or similar attacks).

This matches the criteria for CWE-200: Exposure of Sensitive Information to an Unauthorized Actor.

I will now submit a finding for this vulnerability at the location of should_strip_auth.



